The word ratis seems to have been used by the early writers (Attius and Ennius) for ‘an oar :’ this may have been its original meaning, and would suit well its connection with the root ar or ra, whence come oro, ars. arma, remus, reta, etc. That rates here means Cynthia's vessel only seems more poetical and natural than to suppose with Postgate that Prop. was thinking of a crowd of vessels. storm-stayed by the same storm, and all setting sail together. The interpretation above adopted, by which Cynthia is supposed to sail in spite of high winds,is inconsistent with that view.
